caption: One of my favorite restaurants in the Boston metro. Hot chicken and pickled eggs all day. Gotta get the State Park cocktail.

From the moment  you come to that restaurant  the personel give you an enjoyable feeling. Very warm crew, it is a good place to go out with friends and colleagues or with your date. enjoyable  cuisine, talented  chef, competitive  price and attentive  service. Highly recommended.

This is an awesome combination of a southern bar with a little bit of a divey air. They have different feeling seating arrangements depending on your mood. They have very creative cocktails like the state park cocktail, check it out on the menu, but its like an old fashioned in a beer. They also have old school classics like genny cream. They have excellent southern inspired bar snacks such as boiled peanuts and pickled eggs. Their meals are also delicious, I really like when they have fresh pasta and their nashville hot chicken is intense. Their staff treat you like family and are always a pleasure to be around. Unfortunately their outdoor seating is a little limited, but if you are willing to wait it is worth it.

State Park is an most assuredly an awesome place to come in, have a drink, grab some delicious food, or play some games. The staff is incredibly friendly and helpful and the selection of cocktails is quite notable as well. Quite a few "off the beaten path" liquors can be found behind the bar and, most importantly, the bartenders really know how to mix a drink. The beer selection is good to with rotating draft lines that get changed frequently. I like to come here and shoot a couple of games of pool while exploring their curated jukebox which contains a truly eclectic mix of tunes. The bar also boasts a shufflepuck table (free of charge) as well as two pinball machines. Recently a photo booth was added. It's hard to go wrong with the food as every dish is executed with precision and care. If you're hungry after midnight, you'll find some tasty snacks are served until just before last call. In the warmer months they have two levels of patio seating where you can enjoy your meal and drinks in a vibrant courtyard. There is also live music that gets booked here on Sunday evenings and it is always free of charge. Monday nights you can find John Funke, a DJ who spins records from the 50s, 60s, and occasionally 70s. One thing to note is that the jukebox is unavailable whenever live music is offered. All in all, this place rocks!

Our journey began at the nearby Friendly Toast, which had a two-hour wait... Yah, not on a Sunday at brunch time thank you very much. Mamaleh's Deli next door had 45 minute wait, but recommended State Park, their sister restaurant hidden downstairs for immediate sitting. We lucked out. State Park is a fun retro Americana Dive Bar tucked in the lower level of One Kendall Square. In the heart of The  MIT Technology zone next to Amgen and Akami, you'll find this intimate place with an old school bar, booth seating and a pool table. Food is excellent and service is incredibly friendly. We were welcomed by Glenna at the reception desk, and had great conversations with our servers as well. The vegetarian omelette and brioche french toast were excellent, and based on a suggestion by our server we munched on a delicious pumpkin bread starter. The Great Barrington  coffee also deserves a shout out as being one of the better hose coffees around. Fun relaxed and intimate, I rate State Park an A- for fun, food and atmosphere.

One of my favorite bars in Boston. I love going to the Kendall Square theater and hitting SP before or after. Southern/French fusion bar snacks and sandwiches are the fare, the chicken is great and the burger is too! Cocktail program is on point with a focus on amaro and classic cocktail riffs, I love the State Park cocktail (2-3oz of Rittenhouse and Braulio poured down the neck of a High Life, with a lemon twist) and the beer and shot specials, but anything on the list will be well executed. Only four taps, but they're always filled with good stuff, and there's a larger selection in the lowboy. I'm not much for wine, but the pitchers of sangria (!!!) seem popular. The ambiance and service are what make this place really special - the bartenders and servers are helpful, friendly and attentive. The vintage bar signs and wooden fixtures, soft lighting, games (pool, shuffleboard, pinball) and stocked jukebox are a big part of what keeps me coming back. My go-to for meeting up with old friends or introducing out of towners.
